[2026-03-26T20:06:04.349595] [TOOL_CALL] [write_file] args=() kwargs={'filepath': 'output/adr/ADR-001.md', 'content': "# ADR-001: Technology Stack and Architecture Decisions for To-Do App\n\n## Status\nAccepted\n\n## Date\n2025-01-27\n\n## Context\nWe need to build a To-Do application with the following requirements:\n- User authentication via JWT\n- Full CRUD operations on tasks (title, description, priority, status, due date)\n- A filterable dashboard\n- REST API with Swagger documentation\n- Stack mandated: FastAPI + SQLite + React\n\n## Decisions\n\n### D1: Backend Framework — FastAPI\n**Decision:** Use FastAPI as the backend framework.\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Mandated by project specs\n- Built-in OpenAPI/Swagger documentation at `/docs`\n- Native async support for high performance\n- Pydantic models for request/response validation\n- Dependency injection system ideal for auth middleware\n\n**Consequences:**\n- Python 3.9+ required\n- Team must be familiar with async Python patterns\n- Automatic API documentation reduces documentation effort\n\n### D2: Database — SQLite with SQLAlchemy ORM\n**Decision:** Use SQLite as the database, accessed via SQLAlchemy ORM.\n\n**Rationale:**\n- SQLite mandated by project specs\n- Zero-configuration, file-based database — ideal for single-server deployment\n- SQLAlchemy provides ORM layer for cleaner code and easier migrations\n- Alembic can be used for schema migrations if needed\n\n**Consequences:**\n- No concurrent write scaling (acceptable for a to-do app)\n- Database is a single file — easy backup but no remote DB server\n- SQLAlchemy adds a dependency but provides migration path to PostgreSQL if needed later\n\n**Alternatives considered:**\n- Raw SQL with `sqlite3` module — rejected for lack of ORM benefits and migration support\n- Tortoise ORM — rejected as SQLAlchemy is more mature and widely adopted\n\n### D3: Frontend — React (Single Page Application)\n**Decision:** Use React to build a single-page application (SPA).\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Mandated by project specs\n- Component-based architecture suits the dashboard + forms pattern\n- Rich ecosystem for state management and HTTP clients\n\n**Consequences:**\n- Separate frontend build process (Node.js/npm required for development)\n- Need CORS configuration on FastAPI backend\n- API-first architecture enables future mobile clients\n\n**Sub-decisions:**\n- Use `axios` or `fetch` for HTTP calls to the API\n- Use React Router for client-side routing (login, register, dashboard)\n- Use functional components with hooks (modern React patterns)\n\n### D4: Authentication — JWT with Bearer Token\n**Decision:** Implement JWT-based authentication using `python-jose` and `passlib[bcrypt]`.\n\n**Rationale:**\n- JWT mandated by project specs\n- Stateless authentication — no server-side session storage needed\n- Standard Bearer token scheme works well with SPA frontends\n\n**Consequences:**\n- Tokens must be stored client-side (localStorage or httpOnly cookies)\n- Token expiry must be managed (access token + optional refresh token)\n- Secret key must be configured via environment variable\n\n**Security considerations:**\n- Passwords hashed with bcrypt (via passlib)\n- JWT secret key stored in environment variables, not in code\n- Token expiry set to 30 minutes by default\n- HTTPS recommended for production\n\n### D5: API Design — RESTful with OpenAPI\n**Decision:** Follow REST conventions with automatic OpenAPI/Swagger documentation.\n\n**Rationale:**\n- REST API mandated by project specs\n- FastAPI auto-generates Swagger UI at `/docs`\n- Pydantic schemas ensure request/response validation and documentation\n\n**API Structure:**\n```\nPOST   /api/auth/register    — User registration\nPOST   /api/auth/login        — User login (returns JWT)\nGET    /api/tasks             — List tasks (with filters)\nPOST   /api/tasks             — Create task\nGET    /api/tasks/{id}        — Get task detail\nPUT    /api/tasks/{id}        — Update task\nDELETE /api/tasks/{id}        — Delete task\n```\n\n### D6: Project Structure\n**Decision:** Monorepo with separate `backend/` and `frontend/` directories.\n\n```\n/\n├── backend/\n│   ├── app/\n│   │   ├── main.py           — FastAPI app entry point\n│   │   ├── config.py         — Settings/configuration\n│   │   ├── database.py       — SQLAlchemy engine & session\n│   │   ├── models/           — SQLAlchemy models\n│   │   │   ├── user.py\n│   │   │   └── task.py\n│   │   ├── schemas/          — Pydantic schemas\n│   │   │   ├── user.py\n│   │   │   └── task.py\n│   │   ├── routers/          — API route handlers\n│   │   │   ├── auth.py\n│   │   │   └── tasks.py\n│   │   ├── services/         — Business logic\n│   │   │   ├── auth_service.py\n│   │   │   └── task_service.py\n│   │   └── dependencies.py   — Auth dependency (get_current_user)\n│   ├── tests/\n│   ├── requirements.txt\n│   └── alembic/ (optional)\n├── frontend/\n│   ├── src/\n│   │   ├── components/\n│   │   ├── pages/\n│   │   ├── services/         — API client functions\n│   │   ├── context/          — Auth context\n│   │   └── App.jsx\n│   ├── package.json\n│   └── public/\n├── docker-compose.yml\n└── README.md\n```\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Clear separation of concerns\n- Independent deployment possible\n- Shared repository simplifies development workflow\n\n### D7: Task Data Model\n**Decision:** Task entity with the following fields:\n\n| Field       | Type     | Required | Notes                          |\n|-------------|----------|----------|--------------------------------|\n| id          | Integer  | Auto     | Primary key                    |\n| title       | String   | Yes      | Max 200 chars                  |\n| description | Text     | No       | Optional long text             |\n| priority    | Enum     | Yes      | low, medium, high              |\n| status      | Enum     | Yes      | todo, in_progress, done        |\n| due_date    | DateTime | No       | ISO 8601 format                |\n| created_at  | DateTime | Auto     | Set on creation                |\n| updated_at  | DateTime | Auto     | Updated on modification        |\n| user_id     | Integer  | Auto     | Foreign key to User, set by JWT|\n\n**Rationale:** Directly maps to spec requirements. Enums enforce valid values.\n\n### D8: User Data Model\n**Decision:** User entity with the following fields:\n\n| Field         | Type     | Required | Notes                    |\n|---------------|----------|----------|--------------------------|\n| id            | Integer  | Auto     | Primary key              |\n| email         | String   | Yes      | Unique, used for login   |\n| hashed_password | String | Yes      | bcrypt hash              |\n| created_at    | DateTime | Auto     | Set on creation          |\n\n## Risks\n\n1. **SQLite concurrency:** SQLite has limited write concurrency. Acceptable for a to-do app but would need migration to PostgreSQL for high-traffic scenarios.\n2. **JWT in localStorage:** Vulnerable to XSS attacks. Mitigation: sanitize all inputs, consider httpOnly cookies for production.\n3. **No email verification:** Registration doesn't verify email. Acceptable for MVP scope.\n\n## References\n- FastAPI documentation: https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/\n- SQLAlchemy documentation: https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/\n- JWT best practices: https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7519\n"}
